WEBVTT

00:04.766 --> 00:05.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:05.766 --> 00:07.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:07.266 --> 00:10.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight: the
travel ban at the Supreme Court.

00:10.666 --> 00:15.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Justices agree parts of
President Trump's controversial
executive order can start now,

00:16.800 --> 00:19.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and will hear the
full case in the fall.

00:19.766 --> 00:24.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then: Senate Republicans
scramble to keep their health
care bill alive, releasing a

00:26.233 --> 00:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
revised measure amid wavering
support from within the party.

00:29.433 --> 00:33.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And the first part
of my conversation
with Warren Buffett.

00:33.533 --> 00:38.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We discuss inequality in
the U.S. and America's
shifting role in the world.

00:40.600 --> 00:42.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT, Chairman and
CEO, Berkshire Hathaway: We do
not have quite the percentage

00:42.666 --> 00:46.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the world's GDP that we
had 20 or 30 or 40 years ago,
but we're still the leader.

00:48.666 --> 00:50.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question is whether we
can be the moral leader, as
well as the economic leader.

00:50.166 --> 00:55.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:57.833 --> 01:00.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:00.666 --> 01:05.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: This final day
of the Supreme Court term has
revived a controversial item

01:10.833 --> 01:14.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on President Trump's
agenda: his travel ban.

01:14.033 --> 01:18.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The justices announced that
they will hear arguments this
fall on the constitutionality

01:18.600 --> 01:20.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the ban.

01:20.500 --> 01:24.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the meantime, they reinstated
a limited version of the
order, affecting travelers

01:25.666 --> 01:27.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from six mostly-Muslim
countries.

01:27.866 --> 01:32.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Trump lauded the Supreme
Court's action today as --
quote -- "a clear victory for

01:32.500 --> 01:37.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our national security," adding:
"It allows the travel suspension
for the six terror-prone

01:39.366 --> 01:43.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
countries and the refugee
suspension to become
largely effective."

01:45.100 --> 01:48.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We explore the legal and
practical implications
now with our regular
Supreme Court watcher

01:48.066 --> 01:51.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marcia Coyle of "The National
Law Journal," and Alan Gomez.

01:51.666 --> 01:54.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He covers immigration
for USA Today.

01:54.900 --> 01:55.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

01:55.900 --> 01:57.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Marcia, let's start with you.

01:57.300 --> 01:59.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let's take this one at a time.

01:59.400 --> 02:03.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have got two things that
the court was asked to look at
by the Trump administration,

02:05.166 --> 02:08.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
first to grant review
on hearing the arguments
on the executive order.

02:08.266 --> 02:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National
Law Journal": Right, Judy.

02:10.333 --> 02:14.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The legal challenges
to the executive order
focused on basically two
provisions, the 90-day

02:16.733 --> 02:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
travel ban from six
predominantly Muslim
countries and the 120-day
suspension of the U.S. refugee

02:24.600 --> 02:27.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
assistance program.

02:27.200 --> 02:31.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government asks the
Supreme Court to review
two federal appellate
court rulings that struck

02:33.033 --> 02:37.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down the executive order, one,
and they ruled separately,
claiming that the order violated

02:39.200 --> 02:42.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Establishment Clause of
the constitution because it
was religious discrimination.

02:44.900 --> 02:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a second ground was that
the executive order exceeded
the president's authority under

02:51.733 --> 02:54.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
federal immigration
law, a provision, in
particular, that prohibits
discrimination on the basis

02:57.000 --> 02:59.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of nationality.

02:59.033 --> 03:03.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Supreme Court said it would
hear arguments on the merits
of those two appellate court

03:04.266 --> 03:06.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
rulings in October.

03:06.333 --> 03:09.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, meantime
and, separately, the justices
were also asked by the Trump

03:09.733 --> 03:14.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
administration to lift the
injunctions that had been
imposed on the travel ban.

03:14.400 --> 03:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did they say about that?

03:15.400 --> 03:17.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Right.

03:17.400 --> 03:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
OK, those two federal appellate
courts had approved injunctions
blocking the travel ban

03:21.100 --> 03:26.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and the suspension of
the refugee program.

03:26.000 --> 03:31.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Supreme Court said that the
bans would be lifted only --
would be applied only against

03:35.000 --> 03:40.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
foreign nationals who had
no bona fide relationship
with an individual or
an entity in the United

03:42.666 --> 03:44.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

03:44.633 --> 03:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the court went on to explain
that in terms of a bona fide
relationship, it should be

03:50.833 --> 03:54.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a familial relationship with an
individual or, when it comes to
an entity, a formal documented

03:56.100 --> 04:01.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
relationship, for example, a
student has been accepted at a
university in the United States.

04:03.066 --> 04:06.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, they were
imposing a -- there had to be
some connection already with the

04:06.400 --> 04:07.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
United States.

04:07.400 --> 04:08.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Exactly.

04:08.666 --> 04:10.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For
these individuals.

04:10.166 --> 04:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Three justices disagreed
with this partial listing.

04:12.233 --> 04:14.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What did they say?

04:14.366 --> 04:17.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Justice Thomas
wrote for the dissenters and
was joined by Justices Alito

04:17.466 --> 04:19.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Gorsuch.

04:19.600 --> 04:24.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Justice Thomas explained --
he was most in disagreement
about the partial lifting of

04:25.133 --> 04:27.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the injunctions against
the executive order.

04:27.933 --> 04:32.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said it was unworkable,
that it was going to create a
flood gate of litigation as the

04:32.633 --> 04:37.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government, as government
officials tried to determine
what is a bona fide relationship

04:38.500 --> 04:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with an individual or an entity?

04:40.533 --> 04:45.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those three justices would have
kept -- would have allowed the
ban and the executive order

04:45.966 --> 04:47.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to go into full effect.

04:47.466 --> 04:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Alan
Gomez, let me turn to you.

04:49.133 --> 04:52.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You report, as we said, on
immigration, travel issues.

04:52.433 --> 04:56.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the immediate
effect of this ruling today?

04:56.633 --> 05:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN GOMEZ, USA Today: The
immediate effect is that this
travel ban or what's left of

05:01.266 --> 05:04.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it can go into effect
as early as Thursday.

05:04.766 --> 05:09.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's important to note that,
once it does into effect, this
is going to look very different

05:09.133 --> 05:14.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from what we saw back in
January, when President
Trump first signed his
first travel ban on

05:14.066 --> 05:16.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
January 27.

05:16.133 --> 05:19.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you remember, at the time,
everybody from these countries
was blocked from entering

05:19.733 --> 05:24.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the country, so people were
stranded at U.S. airports or
blocked from getting onto their

05:24.433 --> 05:26.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
U.S.-bound flights overseas.

05:26.900 --> 05:29.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But things have changed
dramatically since then.

05:29.400 --> 05:33.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His revised travel ban
allows for green card
holders to travel, allows
for people who hold

05:33.066 --> 05:35.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
visas to travel.

05:35.166 --> 05:39.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now what the Supreme Court
has ordered, this establishing
this bona fide relationship

05:41.533 --> 05:43.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Marcia was explaining a
second ago, that's where we're
going to start trying to figure

05:43.566 --> 05:46.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
out -- that's where
the government is going
to start trying to
figure out who can come

05:46.866 --> 05:49.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in and who cannot.

05:49.000 --> 05:53.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so there's a lot of gray
area and we do expect to see
some litigation about this,

05:55.966 --> 05:59.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because it's -- it's one thing
if you have a relative in the
U.S. who is trying to claim

05:59.100 --> 06:00.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

06:00.133 --> 06:01.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That person can come in.

06:01.833 --> 06:04.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
If you have a job offer
from a U.S. employer,
that person can come in.

06:04.433 --> 06:08.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what if you're just
businessperson coming over here
to have a couple of meetings on

06:08.200 --> 06:09.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a short-term visa?

06:09.533 --> 06:11.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is that a bona
fide relationship?

06:11.500 --> 06:15.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're a tourist who already
has hotel reservations and
plane reservations, is that

06:15.233 --> 06:17.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a bona fide relationship?

06:17.200 --> 06:19.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's what we're going to
start seeing in those first
couple days when the ban finally

06:19.833 --> 06:21.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
goes into effect.

06:21.066 --> 06:22.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And
that's my question.

06:22.733 --> 06:26.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Just how clear are
these guidelines that
the justices set down?

06:26.433 --> 06:31.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do we assume immigration
officials are scrambling
today to put this in
black and white to figure

06:31.300 --> 06:33.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it out?

06:33.400 --> 06:36.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN GOMEZ: There are a lot of
attorneys within the Department
of Justice and Homeland Security

06:36.100 --> 06:41.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and the State Department
and a lot of immigration
advocacy attorneys who
are just diving into

06:43.066 --> 06:45.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
whatever case law,
whatever precedents they
can find to figure out
what exactly this bona

06:45.600 --> 06:47.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fide relationship is.

06:47.800 --> 06:51.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The justices provided
a few examples that we
have cited already, if
you have a job offer,

06:51.666 --> 06:56.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if you have been admitted
to a U.S. university and if
you have a direct relative.

06:56.333 --> 06:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But beyond that, it's
pretty much wide open now.

06:59.566 --> 07:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we're trying to figure
out what that means.

07:01.900 --> 07:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To give some context here, in
2016, about 108,000 people came
to the United States legally

07:08.166 --> 07:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from these six countries.

07:10.333 --> 07:13.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From a quick accounting of
that, the majority of them will
still be allowed to enter the

07:13.800 --> 07:18.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country under the guidelines
set forth by the Supreme Court,
because most of those were

07:20.233 --> 07:21.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
refugees, had no direct ties
that we're talking about.

07:21.266 --> 07:23.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

07:23.266 --> 07:26.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN GOMEZ: But once we get
into some of that other visa
categories that the relationship

07:26.333 --> 07:30.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a little bit more tenuous,
that is what has to play out
in the next few weeks, to

07:30.233 --> 07:34.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see what government determines
to be a bona fide relationship
and whether the courts agree

07:34.666 --> 07:36.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with them.

07:36.133 --> 07:38.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Very final
quick question, Alan.

07:38.200 --> 07:42.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The travel ban that was issued
by the president last March was
intended to be temporary while

07:43.900 --> 07:46.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the government figured
out vetting procedures.

07:46.333 --> 07:48.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They said it was
going to take 90 days.

07:48.566 --> 07:50.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where does that stand?

07:50.033 --> 07:53.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALAN GOMEZ: Well, that review
finally started last week.

07:53.566 --> 07:57.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In a separate ruling, the
Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in San Francisco sort of

07:57.466 --> 08:02.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
separated that vetting review
from this legal case that we're
going through right now and

08:02.200 --> 08:05.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
said that the administration can
start conducting that review.

08:05.533 --> 08:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In short, what they're trying
to do is gauge what kind of
information we get from foreign

08:10.233 --> 08:13.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
governments to screen people
coming into the country.

08:13.233 --> 08:16.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So they just started
doing that last Monday.

08:16.533 --> 08:18.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so, right, the
clock starts now.

08:18.566 --> 08:22.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have -- they're going to
review it for 20 days, submit
a list to the president.

08:22.500 --> 08:25.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then those governments will have
50 days to get off the list.

08:25.366 --> 08:29.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And at the conclusion
of that vetting review,
then the president can
decide whether he wants

08:29.900 --> 08:33.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to impose more or fewer travel
restrictions against different
countries around the country

08:33.800 --> 08:34.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
- - or world.

08:34.800 --> 08:36.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right.

08:36.200 --> 08:38.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Alan Gomez, USA Today,
Marcia Coyle, thank you both.

08:38.633 --> 08:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: My pleasure, Judy.

08:40.433 --> 08:42.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALAN GOMEZ: Thank you.

08:42.466 --> 08:46.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And in the day's
other news: The Supreme Court
also announced that it will

08:46.133 --> 08:49.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
decide a case pitting gay
rights against religion.

08:49.800 --> 08:54.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At issue is whether
a Denver baker acted
legally when he refused
to sell a same-sex couple

08:55.866 --> 08:57.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a wedding cake.

08:57.100 --> 08:59.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He cited his religious beliefs.

08:59.500 --> 09:04.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In another case, the
justices ruled 7-2 that a
church-run school in Missouri
may seek taxpayer-funded

09:06.133 --> 09:09.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
grants for a new playground.

09:09.300 --> 09:14.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump has again
accused former President
Obama of failing to stop
Russian interference

09:15.033 --> 09:17.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the 2016 election.

09:17.133 --> 09:22.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On Twitter today, he charged:
"The reason that President
Obama did nothing is that he

09:23.300 --> 09:24.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
expected Hillary
Clinton would win.

09:24.666 --> 09:25.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He didn't choke.

09:25.766 --> 09:28.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He colluded or obstructed."

09:28.200 --> 09:33.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump insisted
investigators have no
evidence that his campaign
aides colluded with Russia.

09:35.133 --> 09:39.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
British Prime Minister Theresa
May struck a deal with a
Northern Ireland party today

09:39.400 --> 09:41.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to bolster her
minority government.

09:41.966 --> 09:45.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
May's Conservatives
lost their majority in
this month's election.

09:45.866 --> 09:50.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now they have agreed to provide
some $1.3 billion in extra
funding to Northern Ireland.

09:52.800 --> 09:56.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's in return for the
Democratic Unionist Party's
10 votes in Parliament.

09:58.533 --> 10:02.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
British officials now say that
75 high-rise buildings tested
for fire safety, have failed.

10:03.600 --> 10:07.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The testing began after
London's Grenfell Tower fire.

10:07.100 --> 10:11.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The siding on that building
may have fueled the blaze.

10:11.266 --> 10:14.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The other buildings tested so
far are all over the country.

10:14.866 --> 10:18.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is not clear how long it
will take to fix the problem.

10:18.066 --> 10:23.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In China: Nobel peace laureate
Liu Xiaobo has been released
from prison to a hospital

10:25.333 --> 10:28.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
after being diagnosed with
late-stage liver cancer.

10:28.766 --> 10:31.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Liu has been a leading
dissident for decades.

10:31.433 --> 10:36.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 2009, he was sentenced
to 11 years on a charge
of inciting subversion.

10:37.833 --> 10:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But his lawyer says that
today's release means little.

10:40.500 --> 10:43.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MO SHAOPING, Attorney for Liu
Xiaobo (through translator):
In principle, he will not be

10:43.733 --> 10:47.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allowed to see guests, or
visitors, because of the
special nature of his case.

10:47.833 --> 10:52.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Under medical parole, a
person is still serving a
term while being treated
in a medical facility,

10:52.800 --> 10:54.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
even if it's outside of prison.

10:54.666 --> 10:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Liu Xiaobo's case is special.

10:56.433 --> 10:59.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think the authorities
will allow him to have visitors.

10:59.166 --> 11:04.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Liu won the
Nobel Peace Prize in 2010 for
his efforts demanding greater

11:05.600 --> 11:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
political freedoms and an end
to one-party rule in China.

11:09.433 --> 11:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Back in this country, the
family of Philando Castile has
reached a $3 million settlement

11:15.866 --> 11:18.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over his fatal shooting by
a Minnesota police officer.

11:18.533 --> 11:22.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Castile, a black man, was killed
during a traffic stop last year.

11:22.933 --> 11:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The officer was acquitted
this month of manslaughter
before being fired by
the city of St. Anthony.

11:29.900 --> 11:34.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Takata Corporation has filed
for bankruptcy protection over
faulty air bag inflators linked

11:35.566 --> 11:38.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to at least 16 deaths worldwide.

11:38.533 --> 11:43.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The company faces tens
of billions of dollars
in costs and liabilities
stemming from recalls

11:44.166 --> 11:46.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and lawsuits.

11:46.266 --> 11:50.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The filings today in the U.S.
and Japan clear the way for a
rival company to take over most

11:51.633 --> 11:53.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Takata's assets.

11:53.766 --> 11:58.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On Wall Street today, the Dow
Jones industrial average gained
14 points to close at 21409.

12:00.300 --> 12:05.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Nasdaq fell 18, and the
S&amp;P 500 added a fraction.

12:07.066 --> 12:10.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
a crucial checkup for Republican
senators' health care

12:10.400 --> 12:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bill; showing the Syrian
refugee crisis in a new light
through comic drawings; and much

12:17.133 --> 12:22.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
more.

12:24.200 --> 12:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was a big day in the fight
over health care reform in the
United States and the Senate's

12:34.233 --> 12:36.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
push to replace Obamacare.

12:36.733 --> 12:39.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
John Yang digs in
to the details.

12:39.266 --> 12:43.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Late today,
the Congressional Budget
Office issued its analysis
of the Senate health

12:43.033 --> 12:45.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
care bill.

12:45.566 --> 12:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It found that, by 2026,
22 million more Americans
would be uninsured
than under current law.

12:51.166 --> 12:56.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It would also reduce the
federal deficit by $321
billion over that period.

12:57.966 --> 13:01.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, that estimate of uninsured
Americans is slightly lower
than the CBO projection

13:02.966 --> 13:04.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for the House version,
which passed in May.

13:04.966 --> 13:09.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But a rising tide of opposition
is adding to the difficult
dynamics of trying to pass

13:09.900 --> 13:12.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Senate bill this week.

13:12.033 --> 13:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Joining me now to break all
this down, Julie Rovner.

13:14.533 --> 13:18.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's the chief Washington
correspondent for
Kaiser Health Care News.

13:18.800 --> 13:20.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And our own Lisa Desjardins.

13:20.600 --> 13:22.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Lisa, Julie, thanks
for joining us.

13:22.533 --> 13:25.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Julie, let me start with you.

13:25.600 --> 13:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Drill down a little bit for us
in that number of uninsured.

13:28.733 --> 13:31.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And also what did it say
about the effect on premiums?

13:31.500 --> 13:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER, Kaiser Health
News: Well, basically, what the
CBO said is that even though the

13:34.500 --> 13:38.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senate bill is different in
many, many ways from the House
bill, they end up in roughly

13:38.833 --> 13:41.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the same place in terms
of number of people
who would be uninsured.

13:41.966 --> 13:45.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Basically, both of the bills
would double the percentage
of people without insurance

13:45.433 --> 13:47.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
compared to the
Affordable Care Act.

13:47.633 --> 13:51.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the sort of remarkable
things that it found is that
it would do it for different

13:51.366 --> 13:53.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reasons and in different ways.

13:53.400 --> 13:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For example, the Senate bill
would peg its help with people
paying premiums to a less

13:59.633 --> 14:02.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
valuable plan, a plan
that would pay fewer of
people's medical expenses.

14:02.233 --> 14:06.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they found is that
for a lot of low-income
people, even if they get
help paying the premium,

14:06.066 --> 14:09.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they wouldn't buy insurance
because they wouldn't have any
help using their insurance.

14:09.066 --> 14:13.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The deductibles and
the other cost-sharing
would just be too high.

14:13.033 --> 14:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lisa, you
were just on a conference
call with the CBO.

14:16.433 --> 14:17.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What did you learn?

14:17.933 --> 14:19.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: I think that
is the standout point here.

14:19.333 --> 14:21.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We know who these
uninsured people would be.

14:21.466 --> 14:25.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The 22 million that you just
spoke about, John, those are
mostly low-income Americans

14:25.233 --> 14:26.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and some on the edge
of middle class.

14:26.833 --> 14:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're talking about $30,000
in income for an individual.

14:29.500 --> 14:31.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, that's not poverty.

14:31.000 --> 14:33.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's twice the
level of poverty.

14:33.066 --> 14:37.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The CBO found here that some
of those groups, people making
under $30,000 a year, would

14:37.433 --> 14:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go from about 10 do 15 percent
uninsured, maybe 20 percent,
to maybe 40 percent of the

14:43.966 --> 14:47.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
people making $30,000 or
less would be uninsured
under this plan.

14:47.566 --> 14:49.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, that's a big hit
to that one group.

14:49.700 --> 14:54.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And, Lisa, of
course, you're usually up
on Capitol Hill for us.

14:54.033 --> 14:59.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does this report do to
the calculus of trying to get
50 votes by the end of this

15:00.266 --> 15:01.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
week to pass this
bill in the Senate?

15:01.900 --> 15:04.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Today
started, and it was
already very tough math.

15:04.000 --> 15:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, many of my sources all
day were saying they were not
sure how Senate Leader McConnell

15:07.500 --> 15:08.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
could do it.

15:08.733 --> 15:10.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This makes it even
more difficult.

15:10.033 --> 15:12.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have had reaction
in just the last hour.

15:12.100 --> 15:16.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rand Paul has now said that
he's going to vote not just
against the bill, but to even

15:16.400 --> 15:18.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the idea of bringing it up.

15:18.400 --> 15:22.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a procedural vote that
we expect maybe Wednesday
called motion to proceed.

15:22.166 --> 15:26.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they can't get 51 votes
for even starting this debate
on that bill, it's a very bad

15:26.833 --> 15:28.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
sign.

15:28.733 --> 15:31.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're seeing "makes me
concerned" comments from
Senator Cassidy of Louisiana.

15:31.433 --> 15:33.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
John McCain said this is
obviously not good news.

15:33.900 --> 15:36.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Across the board,
this is definitely not
helping Republicans.

15:36.633 --> 15:38.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not clear how this
gets across the finish line.

15:38.700 --> 15:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And, of course, the
51st vote would likely be the
vice president, who would break

15:41.800 --> 15:43.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a tie.

15:43.866 --> 15:47.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Julie, it wasn't just the CBO
that came out today, but there
were -- so there was other

15:47.500 --> 15:49.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bad news for this
Senate bill today.

15:49.433 --> 15:53.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: Well,
there was also a plethora
of interest groups.

15:53.800 --> 15:58.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Most of the health care industry
has actually come out and
said they really don't -- they

15:58.233 --> 16:00.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
don't like the way this -- the
direction this bill was going.

16:00.800 --> 16:02.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Some of them
vehemently oppose it.

16:02.766 --> 16:05.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some, including like the
National Governors Association
-- this is the bipartisan group

16:05.533 --> 16:08.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
which is barely agrees
on anything -- at least
came out and said we
don't think it should

16:08.866 --> 16:10.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be done this fast.

16:10.966 --> 16:14.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The National Association
of Medicaid Directors,
the people who would
be involved in actually

16:14.400 --> 16:18.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
implementing the change to this
bill, came out with a very,
very strong statement saying

16:18.733 --> 16:22.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that no amount of flexibility
can make up for the dollar
amount of cuts to the Medicaid

16:22.866 --> 16:24.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
program in this bill.

16:24.400 --> 16:26.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
According to the CBO, it's
26 percent over 10 years.

16:26.866 --> 16:29.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: And, Julie,
the Senate made a change
to this bill today.

16:29.666 --> 16:31.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What did they do and
why did they do it?

16:31.266 --> 16:33.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: That's right.

16:33.733 --> 16:36.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Senate -- the original
Senate draft that we
saw last week required
insurers to continue

16:36.700 --> 16:40.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to sell to people who have
preexisting health conditions,
but there was nothing in it to

16:40.733 --> 16:45.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
encourage or urge healthy people
to actually buy insurance.

16:45.233 --> 16:50.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So they put in today or at
least what the CBO scored what
they call a six-month lockout.

16:52.233 --> 16:55.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, if you had any kind of break
in coverage of more than 60
days in the previous 12 months,

16:57.900 --> 16:59.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you would have to wait six
months before you could get
coverage under this new bill.

16:59.800 --> 17:02.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: So, Lisa, you say
we need 50 votes in the Senate.

17:02.300 --> 17:05.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have got five already
saying they're against it.

17:05.700 --> 17:07.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have got a lot on the fence.

17:07.700 --> 17:09.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Who should we be watching?

17:09.766 --> 17:12.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Who will tell us in the
next 48 hours whether or
not this is going to pass?

17:12.433 --> 17:15.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right
now, almost every
Republican senator is key.

17:15.166 --> 17:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the one I'm watching the
most closely is Senator Shelley
Capito of West Virginia.

17:20.900 --> 17:22.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Think about her state.

17:22.433 --> 17:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Trump, President Trump,
won that state by 42 points.

17:25.533 --> 17:30.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If he cannot get a bill across
the finish line in a state
with that much support, there's

17:30.233 --> 17:32.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a real problem.

17:32.166 --> 17:35.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She has serious health
problems in that state, among
them, the opioid epidemic.

17:35.233 --> 17:37.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She wants more money
in this bill for that.

17:37.266 --> 17:38.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We will see if she gets it.

17:38.933 --> 17:40.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But that might not be enough.

17:40.100 --> 17:41.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She has a huge
Medicaid population.

17:41.833 --> 17:43.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She's not the only one, John.

17:43.466 --> 17:45.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I really ran a lot of
the statistics here.

17:45.600 --> 17:47.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Think about this.

17:47.600 --> 17:50.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Almost half of the Republicans
in the Senate have states
where 20 percent of their whole

17:50.900 --> 17:52.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
population is on Medicaid.

17:52.766 --> 17:54.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's something they're taking
very seriously with this bill.

17:54.733 --> 17:58.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Julie, are we likely
to see more changes in this
bill as they try to get to

17:58.233 --> 17:59.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that 50-vote mark?

17:59.233 --> 18:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: Oh, absolutely.

18:01.300 --> 18:04.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One thing that the CBO -- I
guess one piece of good news
for the Republican in the Senate

18:04.333 --> 18:07.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is that the Senate bill
would save considerably more
money than the House bill.

18:07.766 --> 18:09.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, in theory, they
have money to play with.

18:09.766 --> 18:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We would expect more money
to be devoting towards
helping the opioid epidemic.

18:15.600 --> 18:17.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They could make more changes.

18:17.966 --> 18:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem, the difficulty
is that any change
that moves towards the
more moderate numbers

18:20.533 --> 18:24.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will harden the opposition,
the more conservative,
and any change that
make the conservatives

18:24.400 --> 18:26.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
happy will harden the
opposition of the moderates.

18:26.500 --> 18:29.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, question, they only
have two votes to spare.

18:29.000 --> 18:31.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Finding 50 votes,
not an easy thing.

18:31.166 --> 18:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Well, it will be a
drama all week as we get toward
Friday and the self-imposed

18:35.266 --> 18:36.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
deadline.

18:36.633 --> 18:37.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Julie Rovner, Lisa Desjardins,
thank you very much.

18:37.500 --> 18:38.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JULIE ROVNER: Thank you.

18:38.766 --> 18:40.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And
thank you, John.

18:40.800 --> 18:44.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And as we have heard, a number
of patient groups and major
players in the health care

18:44.300 --> 18:46.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
industry have opposed
the Senate bill.

18:46.800 --> 18:50.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Every major hospital
group has criticized it.

18:50.033 --> 18:54.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They say they are especially
worried about deep reductions
in Medicaid spending for the

18:54.500 --> 18:59.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
poor and those with
disabilities, changes
that include new limits
like spending caps

18:59.366 --> 19:04.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or block grants that would
eventually cut the number
of people on Medicaid.

19:04.266 --> 19:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
