in bus shelters all

29:01.800 --> 29:04.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
over Vancouver, Canada.

29:04.666 --> 29:09.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHON DALTON: By drawing
people as cartoons, I
think you can engage the
reader to see themselves

29:14.533 --> 29:16.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the story.

29:16.533 --> 29:19.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: But it's about
more than putting yourself
in a refugee's shoes.

29:19.166 --> 29:24.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For Mohammed, comics have the
power to animate a humanitarian
crisis many have grown numb

29:24.633 --> 29:26.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to.

29:26.666 --> 29:30.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: When you
try your best to share a story
about the worst crisis after

29:32.600 --> 29:37.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
World War II, sometimes, you
feel that language is not
actually capable of doing that.

29:38.733 --> 29:40.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JONATHON DALTON: I think
that's what I drew.

29:40.800 --> 29:45.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: After shooting the
protest footage, Mohammed had
no idea his future would take

29:45.100 --> 29:46.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a dark turn.

29:46.766 --> 29:50.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: I
tried my best to say
out of trouble, but...

29:50.100 --> 29:55.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: Assad's security
forces stormed Mohammed's
classroom as he was writing an

29:55.066 --> 29:56.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exam.

29:56.600 --> 29:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He was charged with terrorism
for documenting the uprising.

29:58.933 --> 30:03.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: Those pictures
that I was able to upload
were all over the news, all

30:05.166 --> 30:07.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
over the world.

30:07.700 --> 30:10.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: Mohammed
was blindfolded and
shuttled off to one of the
regime's many detention

30:10.933 --> 30:12.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
centers.

30:12.966 --> 30:16.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the next 150 days, the
guards would deprive him of food
and sleep, chain him from the

30:18.100 --> 30:22.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ceiling and beat him
inside of a tire.

30:22.466 --> 30:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when he wasn't being
tortured, he was crammed into
small rooms with dozens of other

30:27.400 --> 30:28.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
prisoners.

30:28.633 --> 30:32.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH:
I survived, yes.

30:32.700 --> 30:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They managed to change me.

30:34.000 --> 30:39.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They managed to terrorize me.

30:41.033 --> 30:44.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: Mohammed was
released from prison when
his brother bribed a judge.

30:44.233 --> 30:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: When I got
my freedom back, all I wanted
to do was see my family.

30:50.600 --> 30:53.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I also wanted to say goodbye.

30:53.333 --> 30:56.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I needed to get as
far away as I could.

30:56.766 --> 31:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: He jumped into
a taxi and fled to Lebanon.

31:00.900 --> 31:05.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: When you're
on survival mode, like where
you're not whole, it was

31:08.500 --> 31:12.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
because of that, that I
decided to leave Syria.

31:12.900 --> 31:17.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was because of that I decided
that I'm not going to risk
being detained and tortured

31:19.633 --> 31:21.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
again.

31:21.766 --> 31:25.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEFAN LABBE: He would soon be
chosen as one of the first 200
Syrian refugees to be granted

31:26.366 --> 31:28.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
asylum in Canada.

31:28.433 --> 31:32.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: When I
arrived in Vancouver, I had
only the clothes on my back.

31:34.033 --> 31:37.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
STEFAN LABBE: Three
years on, he's built a
life for himself here.

31:37.433 --> 31:42.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now Mohammed helps other
refugees newly arrived
in the city, people like
Osama, who just arrived

31:43.833 --> 31:46.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from Syria with his
wife and four kids.

31:46.566 --> 31:49.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Today, Mohammed is
helping them start over.

31:49.333 --> 31:54.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He signs them up for health
insurance, helps them open a
bank account, and teaches them

31:58.233 --> 32:00.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
how to withdraw
money from an ATM.

32:00.966 --> 32:03.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: Withdraw.

32:03.066 --> 32:08.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEFAN LABBE: But with
the cartoon project, he
wants to reach beyond
the refugee community.

32:10.000 --> 32:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ALSALEH: I think it's
very important to, you know,
share my story, other immigrants

32:16.400 --> 32:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to share their stories as well,
in order to demonstrate we have
this beautiful place because

32:24.500 --> 32:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we welcome others, because
we are the positive example
in a -- in a very bad world.

32:33.533 --> 32:38.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEFAN LABBE: With his
family scattered across
Turkey and Germany, and
anti-immigrant movements

32:40.366 --> 32:43.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the size, Mohammed is
focused on one thing, reuniting
his family here in Canada.

32:47.300 --> 32:52.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Stefan Labbe in Vancouver.

32:53.933 --> 32:57.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next, to
part one of my interview
with Warren Buffett.

33:04.100 --> 33:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's one of the shrewdest and
most successful investors in
the world, earning the nickname

33:08.800 --> 33:10.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Oracle of Omaha.

33:10.733 --> 33:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I traveled to Nebraska
last week for this
wide-ranging conversation.

33:15.066 --> 33:20.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a note: Buffett is CBO of
Berkshire Hathaway, which owns
BNSF Railway, one of the funders

33:21.400 --> 33:23.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the "NewsHour."

33:23.933 --> 33:28.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's number two on Forbes'
list of the world's
wealthiest people, worth
more than $75 billion.

33:31.800 --> 33:36.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Warren Buffett is an
investing rock star to
his Berkshire Hathaway
shareholders, who gather

33:37.533 --> 33:39.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Omaha every year.

33:39.800 --> 33:43.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One share is trading
today at $251,000.

33:43.933 --> 33:48.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Two years ago, the legendary
firm celebrated its record of
investment over a half-century,

33:51.100 --> 33:56.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a portfolio that includes Kraft
Heinz, Geico, Wells Fargo,
Coca-Cola and, among others,

33:58.733 --> 34:01.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Nebraska Furniture Mart.

34:01.100 --> 34:04.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the largest furniture
store in North America.

34:04.800 --> 34:09.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Buffet bought it in 1983
from Rose Blumkin, a
Russian immigrant who
built it from nothing.

34:11.733 --> 34:13.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT, Chairman
and CEO, Berkshire Hathaway:
There's nothing like it.

34:13.833 --> 34:16.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we're the 58th market in the
United States, and this was the
largest home furnishing store

34:16.066 --> 34:19.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in the country, until
we built two more.

34:19.000 --> 34:20.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why
was she so successful?

34:20.800 --> 34:22.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What was the secret?

34:22.833 --> 34:26.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: She would say --
she had a thing in her office,
which you probably couldn't

34:28.700 --> 34:31.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
read, but it says she
had two things, sell
cheap and tell the truth.

34:31.300 --> 34:36.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We talked on the
showroom floor surrounded by
sofas, lamps and coffee tables.

34:37.833 --> 34:41.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The state of the economy
was our first topic.

34:41.100 --> 34:43.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The stock market's booming.

34:43.433 --> 34:48.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Unemployment rate is,
what, is as low as it's
been in 15, 16 years.

34:48.033 --> 34:52.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we're still not
seeing the growth that
people would like to see.

34:52.133 --> 34:54.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What's going on?

34:54.166 --> 34:56.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: The economy
is doing well, but all
Americans aren't doing well.

34:56.333 --> 35:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we have got $57,000 or
$58,000 of GDP per person.

35:02.766 --> 35:04.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is a lot of stuff.

35:04.733 --> 35:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And yet
the growth, the rate of
growth is, what, 2 percent.

35:08.233 --> 35:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Yes, 2 percent.

35:10.333 --> 35:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Trump
is saying we're going to get
it up a lot higher than that.

35:13.400 --> 35:14.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is that doable?

35:14.933 --> 35:17.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well, it may
be occasionally it happens.

35:17.033 --> 35:20.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, no, I don't think
probably on average we will
have that kind of growth.

35:20.666 --> 35:23.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But 2 percent does
wonders for you, Judy.

35:23.300 --> 35:27.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you take 2 percent,
we have a half-a-percent
population growth, and we
have a little immigration,

35:27.300 --> 35:32.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but 2 percent in one generation
will add $19,000 of GDP per
person, family of four, $76,000

35:36.533 --> 35:38.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in one generation.

35:38.600 --> 35:42.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, your children and
your children's children
and all that, they
will live far, far, far

35:43.700 --> 35:45.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
better than we live
with 2 percent growth.

35:45.766 --> 35:49.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me
then ask you a little bit about
the employment picture, because

35:49.033 --> 35:51.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it is, as you ISIS
, low unemployment.

35:51.633 --> 35:54.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
People -- a lot of
people have jobs.

35:54.100 --> 35:57.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, we're
told the labor participation
rate is lower than what
the experts like it

36:00.366 --> 36:01.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to be.

36:01.300 --> 36:02.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WARREN BUFFETT: Yes.

36:02.833 --> 36:04.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: More people are
leaving jobs than are joining.

36:04.366 --> 36:07.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Are we seeing some
kind of shift?

36:07.166 --> 36:09.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well, we always
see shifts in employment.

36:09.266 --> 36:13.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you think about it, if you go
back to 1800, it took 80 percent
of the labor force to produce

36:14.633 --> 36:17.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
enough food for the country.

36:17.500 --> 36:19.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Now it takes less
than 3 percent.

36:19.166 --> 36:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, the truth is that market
systems move people around.

36:22.800 --> 36:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You also see,
though, some experts saying
that not enough -- there aren't

36:27.533 --> 36:32.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enough workers out there who
know -- who have the skills to
do all the jobs that are needed.

36:33.933 --> 36:35.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well,
there's always a mismatch.

36:35.566 --> 36:40.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I mean, you know, as
the economy evolves, it
reallocates resources.

36:42.466 --> 36:46.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, the real problem, in my
view, is -- this has been -- the
prosperity has been unbelievable

36:47.166 --> 36:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for the extremely rich people.

36:49.900 --> 36:54.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you go to 1982, when Forbes
put on their first 400 list,
those people had $93 billion.

36:56.733 --> 37:01.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They now they have $2.4
trillion, 25 for one.

37:01.066 --> 37:06.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That is -- this has
been a prosperity that's
been disproportionately
rewarding to the people

37:07.266 --> 37:08.900 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on top.

37:08.900 --> 37:11.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Are we
stuck forever with some
measure inequality?

37:11.033 --> 37:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: No, we generally
have translated greater output
in the few hours of work per

37:18.500 --> 37:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
week over the last century.

37:21.233 --> 37:23.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's a good
trend of the future.

37:23.500 --> 37:28.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we do have to have a system
that, as output of goods and
services keeps increasing per

37:30.500 --> 37:34.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
capita, that it takes care of
the people who are willing to
work and really are not getting

37:34.566 --> 37:37.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by very well with a
family on a 40-hour week.

37:37.533 --> 37:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You come
across as optimistic about
the future of this country.

37:41.833 --> 37:44.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

37:44.433 --> 37:45.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think you
wrote to your shareholders
last year it's been a
mistake to bet against

37:45.666 --> 37:48.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the United States for
the last 240 years.

37:48.866 --> 37:53.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Has the U.S. standing, though,
in the world been -- has it
been changed, has it been harmed

37:55.833 --> 37:59.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in any way, given what's
been going on for the
last six or eight months?

37:59.066 --> 38:04.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: We do not
have quite the percentage
of the world's GDP
that we had 20 or 30 or

38:05.166 --> 38:07.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
40 years ago, but
we're still the leader.

38:07.266 --> 38:10.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question is whether we
can be the moral leader, as
well as the economic leader.

38:10.266 --> 38:12.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And
what do you think?

38:12.133 --> 38:14.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well,
I think that's a podium
that we should have.

38:14.800 --> 38:19.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We will be the economic
leader, and we should
be the moral leader.

38:21.466 --> 38:23.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We should stand for more
than the fact that we're
the wealthiest country.

38:23.633 --> 38:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And do you
think we are right now?

38:25.733 --> 38:28.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well, sometimes,
we are and sometimes we aren't.

38:28.433 --> 38:30.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:30.433 --> 38:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: I didn't think
what happened on the Paris
agreement was a good idea.

38:35.600 --> 38:36.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have to live with
the rest of the world.

38:36.533 --> 38:39.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's a mistake, in my view.

38:39.600 --> 38:41.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trade has generally
developed in this country.

38:41.633 --> 38:44.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We actually export 12 or
13 percent of our GDP.

38:44.633 --> 38:46.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was only 5 percent in 1970.

38:46.766 --> 38:48.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But it benefits us.

38:48.000 --> 38:49.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It benefits the
rest of the world.

38:49.466 --> 38:51.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't benefit the
steelworker maybe in Ohio.

38:51.833 --> 38:55.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's the problem that has
to be addressed, because when
you have something that's good

38:55.566 --> 39:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for society, but terribly
harmful for given individuals,
we have got to make sure those

39:00.133 --> 39:02.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
individuals are taken care of.

39:02.200 --> 39:05.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me ask
you about a couple questions
about markets, investing.

39:05.533 --> 39:08.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, nobody knows
markets better than you do.

39:08.500 --> 39:12.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think you said earlier this
year that you weren't worried
that the market was in a bubble,

39:12.200 --> 39:14.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
because interest rates
were staying low.

39:14.833 --> 39:17.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
As you know, the Federal Reserve
is starting to raise them.

39:17.333 --> 39:19.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you still feel the
