even more than taxes.

43:07.100 --> 43:11.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WARREN BUFFETT: Well, it
does, I mean, in terms of our
competitiveness in the world.

43:11.700 --> 43:16.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Health care in 1960
was 5 percent of GDP.

43:16.266 --> 43:17.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And there's only 100
cents in the dollar.

43:17.966 --> 43:22.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's gone from 5 cents
-- 5 percent to 17 percent.

43:22.866 --> 43:24.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it keeps going up.

43:24.833 --> 43:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Corporate taxes have gone down
from 4 percent to 2 percent.

43:28.733 --> 43:33.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, corporate taxes are
way less of a factor in
American competitiveness
than -- I'm talking

43:34.933 --> 43:38.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
about overall business
-- than medical costs.

43:38.000 --> 43:42.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And as
we sit here today in
Omaha, the Republicans
in Congress are madly

43:42.866 --> 43:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
